Source file is "Source_Video.mkv".
Prerequisites :
- An access to an Unix environment (VM or not)
- Tesseract (version 3.03+ recommended) and its English dictionnary (Unix) : https://github.com/tesseract-ocr/tesseract
- Links (Unix) : http://links.twibright.com/
- Simple X Image Viewer (Unix) : https://github.com/muennich/sxiv
- xdotool (Linux) : http://www.semicomplete.com/projects/xdotool/
- GNU Parallel (version 20131122+ recommended) (Unix) : http://www.gnu.org/software/parallel/
- Perl (Unix) : https://www.perl.org/
- FFmpeg (Unix, and optionally Windows) : https://www.ffmpeg.org/
- Vapoursynth R27+ (Unix or Windows) : http://www.vapoursynth.com/
- Vapoursynth's FFMS2 plugin (Unix or Windows) : https://github.com/FFMS/ffms2/releases
- Vapoursynth's GenericFilters plugin (included in Vapoursynth Windows) (Unix or Windows) : https://github.com/myrsloik/GenericFilters
- Vapoursynth's HAvsFunc plugin (Unix or Windows) : http://forum.doom9.org/showthread.php?t=166582
- Vapoursynth's SceneChange plugin (Unix or Windows) : http://forum.doom9.org/showthread.php?t=166769
- Vapoursynth's fmtconv plugin (Unix or Windows) : http://forum.doom9.org/showthread.php?t=166504
- (Optional) Vapoursynth's nnedi3 plugin (Unix or Windows) : http://forum.doom9.org/showthread.php?t=166434

Installation script for all the prerequisites on Debian Jessie and LMDE Betsy :
sh YoloDebInstallation.sh eng-only

Vapoursynth PPA for Ubuntu and Linux Mint (not tested) : https://launchpad.net/~djcj/+archive/ubuntu/vapoursynth

Tip : You can install Vapoursynth and its plugins on Windows. Filtering will be faster than on a Linux VM.

/!\ If you build Vapoursynth on Ubuntu 14.04 or Linux Mint 17, please use Kyrill's ffmpeg debs : https://launchpad.net/~kirillshkrogalev/+archive/ubuntu/ffmpeg-next
Then install libavcodec-ffmpeg-dev, instead of libavcodec-dev etc...

The OCR procedure consists of two steps :
First, you'll have to filter the video with Vapoursynth on the environment of your choice. Don't forget to edit the first lines in YoloCR.vpy according to your source file.
vspipe -y YoloCR.vpy - | ffmpeg -i - -c:v mpeg4 -qscale:v 3 -y Filtered_Video.mp4
You now have an OCR-isable video and scenechange informations.
Then you can OCR the video on the Unix environment.
./YoloCR.sh Filtered_Video.mp4
Now it's Checking time :D

